WEBVTT

00:00.034 --> 00:03.698
The following message by Alistair Begg is made available by Truth For Life.

00:04.498 --> 00:08.462
For more information visit us online at truthforlife.org.

00:09.704 --> 00:14.969
Let me read to you from 2 Timothy and chapter 2 beginning at verse 1.

00:15.409 --> 00:27.922
You then, my child, be strengthened by the grace that is in Christ Jesus and what you've heard from me in the presence of many witnesses in trust of faithful men who will be able to teach others also.

00:28.546 --> 00:31.609
Share in suffering as a good soldier of Christ Jesus.

00:32.390 --> 00:38.537
No soldier gets entangled in civilian pursuits, since his aim is to please the one who enlisted him.

00:39.618 --> 00:43.643
An athlete is not crowned unless he competes according to the rules.

00:44.183 --> 00:47.927
It is the hard-working farmer who want to have the first share of the crops.

00:48.768 --> 00:53.013
Think over what I say, for the Lord will give you understanding in everything.

00:54.174 --> 00:57.458
Remember Jesus Christ, risen from the dead.

00:57.698 --> 01:04.846
the offspring of David, as preached in my gospel for which I am suffering bound with chains as a criminal.

01:05.827 --> 01:07.529
But the word of God is not bound.

01:08.330 --> 01:16.859
Therefore, I endure everything for the sake of the elect, that they also may obtain the salvation that is in Christ Jesus with eternal glory.

01:17.640 --> 01:19.021
The saying is trustworthy.

01:19.802 --> 01:23.266
For if we have died with him, we will also live with him.

01:23.987 --> 01:26.930
If we endure, we will also reign with him,

01:27.394 --> 01:30.578
If we deny Him, He also will deny us.

01:31.380 --> 01:36.306
If we are faithless, He remains faithful, for He cannot deny Himself.

01:37.548 --> 01:47.302
Remind them of these things and charge them before God not to quarrel about words which does no good, but only ruins the hearers.

01:48.403 --> 01:55.954
Do your best to present yourself to God as one approved a worker who has no need to be ashamed

01:56.354 --> 01:58.897
rightly handling the word of truth.

02:00.900 --> 02:02.943
Thanks be to God for His word.

02:03.864 --> 02:04.485
A brief prayer.

02:04.865 --> 02:09.171
Father, with our Bibles open, what we know not, teach us.

02:10.833 --> 02:13.056
What we have not, give us.

02:14.298 --> 02:16.601
What we are not, make us.

02:17.822 --> 02:19.344
For your Son's sake, we pray.

02:19.384 --> 02:20.786
Amen.

02:22.946 --> 02:33.800
Well, in turning to this familiar passage in Second Timothy, I think some of you will have immediately determined that we're going to deal with these early metaphors, which are so familiar to us.

02:33.940 --> 02:48.518
The leader in the church, the pastor in the church, the Christian is supposed to be identifiable with all of the characteristics of an Olympic athlete or a hard-working farmer or a soldier under his commanding officer.

02:49.299 --> 02:51.762
But we're not going to.

02:51.906 --> 02:56.592
As you read on through the chapter, you discover that Paul is still employing pictures.

02:57.554 --> 03:03.922
He introduces the issue of the way the servant is supposed to be towards the end of the chapter.

03:03.982 --> 03:12.574
And prior to that, the picture of a vessel or of a piece of porcelain or hardware that was in a home that was set aside for use.

03:13.375 --> 03:21.746
And then prior to that, and in verse 15 particularly, the picture of the church leader of the pastor

03:21.890 --> 03:24.334
as a worker, as a worker.

03:25.275 --> 03:40.778
Now, it's pretty common for me, and presumably for you as well, if you're in pastoral ministry or considering it, to be on the receiving end of people saying immediately when you identify yourself in that way, or what is it like to work just one day a week?

03:41.739 --> 03:46.286
And we have to then do our very best to try and explain that that is not the case.

03:47.087 --> 03:49.330
Although some of you young guys who are spending

03:49.410 --> 03:59.145
A significant part of the week with a laptop and Starbucks are arguably justifiably accused, but I'll leave you to work that out between yourself and God.

03:59.205 --> 04:01.714
You certainly couldn't call that pastoral visitation.

04:01.794 --> 04:09.305
or hospital visitation, but anyway, the fact of the matter is we know that there's more to the task despite what people say.

04:09.665 --> 04:17.356
Mark Twain in Huckleberry Finn writes a wonderful passage, remember where Hock is engaged with Joanna.

04:17.697 --> 04:21.362
He's got himself tied up in knots because he's been telling lies again.

04:21.422 --> 04:28.272
He's telling lies about this particular church and who was where and whatnot and got himself in a dreadful mess.

04:28.292 --> 04:30.034
And in the course of the dialogue,

04:30.146 --> 04:34.351
Joanna says about this minister, well, where was he?

04:34.371 --> 04:35.593
And he wasn't where he should be.

04:35.653 --> 04:40.418
And so Haq immediately says, well, you know, there's more than one preacher.

04:40.479 --> 04:44.123
There's not only one preacher for each church.

04:44.964 --> 04:48.749
And Joanna says, why would he want more than one?

04:48.789 --> 04:51.132
And says, Haq, what?

04:51.852 --> 04:53.334
To preach off for a king?

04:53.354 --> 04:55.857
I never saw such a girl as you.

04:56.498 --> 04:59.762
They don't have any fewer than 17 preachers.

05:00.418 --> 05:02.000
Seventeen, my word.

05:02.720 --> 05:05.664
Why, I wouldn't be able to sit there and listen to them all.

05:06.344 --> 05:11.090
Even if it did mean I couldn't go to heaven, it must take them a whole week to finish the service.

05:12.191 --> 05:15.314
Shocks, they don't all preach on the same day.

05:15.835 --> 05:16.896
Only one of them does.

05:18.658 --> 05:20.760
Well, then, what do the rest of them do?

05:22.122 --> 05:22.682
Oh, not much.

05:23.964 --> 05:27.347
They sit around, pass the collection plate, that kind of stuff.

05:28.448 --> 05:29.970
But usually they don't do anything.

05:31.266 --> 05:32.628
Well, then what are they there for?

05:33.890 --> 05:34.270
Why?

05:34.290 --> 05:36.433
They're there for style.

05:39.077 --> 05:40.199
Don't you know nothing?

05:41.821 --> 05:43.443
They're there for style.

05:46.247 --> 05:47.609
But we're not there for style.

05:48.831 --> 05:52.697
We're there because we are workers and workers in the Word.

05:53.638 --> 05:59.346
And it is with this work in the Word that Paul is particularly concerned in relationship

05:59.554 --> 06:06.443
to Timothy, the church in every generation is in urgent need of pastors who will study.

06:08.086 --> 06:13.333
The pace of contemporary life makes it an increasingly difficult goal to achieve.

06:14.614 --> 06:23.426
But effective teaching of the Bible is absolutely fundamental to the task to which we're called.

06:24.328 --> 06:29.074
And if the congregation is to gain any understanding of the Word of God,

06:29.218 --> 06:33.443
then the place of the pastor's personal study is of vital importance.

06:34.224 --> 06:42.814
If, as pastors, we are constantly pouring out without pouring in, we will soon cease to pour out anything of value at all."

06:43.756 --> 06:51.725
Said Spurgeon, if we do not spend time in diligent study, our congregations will get poverty-stricken sermons.

06:52.847 --> 06:54.088
Poverty-stricken sermons.

06:54.128 --> 06:58.994
And then in addressing his students humorously, he says, I have heard of a brother.

06:59.522 --> 07:02.465
who trusts in the Lord and does not study.

07:03.847 --> 07:06.850
But I have also heard that his people do not trust him.

07:06.890 --> 07:13.237
In fact, I am informed that they wish him to go elsewhere with his inspired discourses.

07:14.038 --> 07:18.603
For they say that when he did study, his talk was poor enough.

07:19.564 --> 07:26.071
But now that he gives them that which comes first to his lips, it is altogether unbearable.

07:27.092 --> 07:28.594
If any man will preach,

07:28.674 --> 07:36.983
as he should preach, his work will take more out of him than any other labor under heaven."

07:37.984 --> 07:39.766
That's quite a statement.

07:39.786 --> 07:48.836
If a man will preach as he ought to preach, then his work will take more out of him than any other labor under heaven.

07:49.877 --> 07:57.906
So Paul addresses Timothy, and by derivation, every pastor and Christian leader, I guess, as a worker

07:58.018 --> 08:05.811
whose personal goal must be to present himself to God as one worker who does not need to be ashamed.

08:06.753 --> 08:10.299
Now, that 15th verse usually stands on its own, but it's not on its own.

08:10.599 --> 08:14.566
It follows verse 15 and actually precedes verse 16.

08:15.227 --> 08:20.075
We won't worry about 16, we don't have time, but let's look at 14 and 15.

08:20.756 --> 08:24.242
First of all, the directive is remind them

08:24.610 --> 08:28.335
That is the pastor's responsibility for his flock.

08:28.976 --> 08:37.088
And then in verse 15, present yourself that is his responsibility on his own behalf.

08:37.789 --> 08:40.594
So we'll deal with them each in turn.

08:41.335 --> 08:43.338
First of all then, remind them.

08:43.358 --> 08:49.126
Timothy is working in a context in which people are intrigued by error.

08:49.787 --> 08:51.730
They are disinterested in truth.

08:52.066 --> 08:54.589
and they are allured by all kinds of myths.

08:55.630 --> 09:13.332
Therefore, it must have been tempting for him, perhaps to play the game of the false teachers, especially those who had proved to be successful by catering to the itching-year syndrome, to giving to his congregation and his listeners what they wanted to hear.

09:13.392 --> 09:17.417
And Paul is heading him off of the past, and he says, you mustn't do that.

09:17.817 --> 09:21.682
You must remind these people of the essentials of the faith.

09:21.858 --> 09:23.922
remind them of these things.

09:25.145 --> 09:29.815
He has already begun immediately to address Timothy with the priority of the gospel.

09:29.875 --> 09:35.868
He has invited Timothy to engage in pastoral ministry with the amazing and amazing welcome.

09:36.209 --> 09:39.255
Join me in suffering for the gospel.

09:39.716 --> 09:42.482
That's his invitation to pastoral ministry.

09:42.722 --> 09:45.385
Join me in suffering for the gospel.

09:45.685 --> 09:47.747
Not an invitation to go and have a holiday.

09:47.767 --> 09:50.970
It's not an invitation to let people hear you speak.

09:51.330 --> 09:57.997
It is an invitation that he gives to him to engage in the same activity and in a context that is demanding.

09:58.577 --> 10:11.570
And if he's going to do that, then he's going to be again and again reminding his listeners of the death of Jesus on the cross that it is satisfied the justice of God so that we may become the children of God

10:11.746 --> 10:15.611
and so that we might then live and love the Lord Jesus.

10:16.512 --> 10:37.778
And I want to say to you that in our day, in a day when people are confused about what to believe, doctrinally, and how to behave morally, the last thing they need from you as a potential pastor or as a pastor or from me is one novel idea after another.

10:38.658 --> 10:46.147
I'm always really disheartened when people will say of someone, you know, he is able to make the Bible relevant.

10:47.208 --> 10:47.809
No, he's not.

10:49.591 --> 10:51.132
And neither are you, and neither am I.

10:51.913 --> 10:53.415
We don't make the Bible relevant.

10:53.836 --> 10:56.999
Our task is to show how relevant the Bible is.

10:57.900 --> 11:02.866
And many a man in a quest for relevance has made himself entirely irrelevant.

11:03.458 --> 11:16.996
Now we're to feed the flock of God by proclaiming the whole ounce of God, the whole counsel of God, and not as ends in themselves, but in order that we might as Paul says elsewhere in Colossians, present everyone mature in Christ Jesus.

11:18.839 --> 11:32.818
Now the constant and the regular exposition of the gospel, that is all that God has done for us in Christ, focuses our attention on God's mercy, which in turn instills gratitude

11:33.218 --> 11:36.383
which in turn leads to obedience and to growth.

11:37.444 --> 11:41.430
You check that out and think about it as you're pondering these things later on.

11:41.811 --> 11:57.074
As we continue to proclaim the gospel, it focuses our attention on the mercy of God, which instills in the heart of the child of God gratitude, which then reveals itself in the child of God in obedience and in growth.

11:57.698 --> 11:59.922
I wish I had understood that when I was a younger man.

12:00.282 --> 12:10.139
I think I wasted a lot of time in the early days of my ministry, rebuking believers for their failures, rather than setting before them the objective of Christ-likeness.

12:11.502 --> 12:14.627
And that as a privilege, not simply as a duty.

12:15.729 --> 12:18.834
In other words, being like God, in that wonderful hymn

12:18.978 --> 12:20.920
It begins, praise my soul, the king of heaven.

12:20.940 --> 12:23.323
You have that wonderful verse.

12:23.683 --> 12:27.227
Praise him for his grace and favor to our fathers in distress.

12:27.607 --> 12:29.650
And praise him still the same forever.

12:29.970 --> 12:34.935
Here's the line, slow to chide and swift to bless.

12:35.776 --> 12:38.339
He's slow to chide and he's swift to bless.

12:38.379 --> 12:42.183
Some of us in pastoral ministry have got that completely upside down.

12:43.224 --> 12:46.167
We're quick to chide and slow to bless.

12:47.149 --> 12:48.530
And the pastor's goal

12:48.770 --> 12:55.579
is the holiness and is the unreserved obedience to Christ of Himself and of all of the believers.

12:56.500 --> 13:16.146
And the wonderful thing, of course, and that's why the reminder is so necessary, is that God's Spirit does His work through God's Word, enabling the people of God to do things that otherwise they couldn't do, to love their enemies, because they realized that God loved them when they were His enemy, to forgive others, because God has forgiven us.

13:16.578 --> 13:19.341
And so he says, I want you to keep NIV.

13:19.361 --> 13:21.843
Keep reminding them of these things.

13:24.045 --> 13:27.689
Then he says, and you also need to charge them before God.

13:28.349 --> 13:39.640
In other words, if there are things that they mustn't forget, there are also certain things that they must be prepared to forsake, and particularly this preoccupation with quarrelsome-ness.

13:40.982 --> 13:45.426
The solemnity of it is undeniable, isn't it, and charge them before God?

13:46.242 --> 13:47.844
in the presence of God, he says.

13:48.504 --> 13:49.745
He does that again and again.

13:49.785 --> 13:55.591
It's a contrast, isn't it, with the weightlessness of so much contemporary Christianity?

13:58.614 --> 13:59.995
You go to the average funeral.

14:00.636 --> 14:04.840
You could be forgiven for thinking that somehow or another, you are at his 21st birthday party.

14:06.121 --> 14:08.503
There's a world these slides and everything here for.

14:09.784 --> 14:10.805
I thought the guy died.

14:12.867 --> 14:13.568
You know, he died.

14:13.648 --> 14:15.890
Yeah, but we don't want to think about the fight that he died.

14:16.546 --> 14:17.047
Why not?

14:18.088 --> 14:19.150
Haven't you read your Bible?

14:20.051 --> 14:28.703
Don't you know that it is better to go to a house of mourning than to a party because death is the destiny of every man and the living must bring that to heart?

14:30.085 --> 14:33.830
When's the last time you saw a contemporary church build a graveyard on its property?

14:35.913 --> 14:36.333
Why not?

14:38.216 --> 14:45.426
Solemnity, solemnity in praise that doesn't impact exuberance, doesn't impact joy,

14:45.954 --> 14:47.436
But it makes it perfectly clear.

14:48.317 --> 14:54.524
What is happening here is an encounter between the living God and those who are His servants.

14:54.604 --> 15:10.002
It's a really sad experience, loved ones, to gather with the people of God when we travel and to feel that those who are leading us, either from their preaching or from the praise, are too close to the laughing grave diggers in Hamlet.

15:10.818 --> 15:16.144
of whom you will remember when is it a hamlet and learties or whoever it is.

15:16.184 --> 15:20.910
They come on them and they find them and they're singing and they're joking and they're laughing.

15:21.390 --> 15:28.999
And one says to the other, how is it that gravediggers can be like this in such a job?

15:29.019 --> 15:38.450
And the reply is, custom hath made of it for them a matter of easiness.

15:39.074 --> 15:42.038
In other words, it's just so routine to them.

15:42.579 --> 15:45.643
Now, clearly, the grave devil can't cry in every funeral.

15:46.704 --> 15:50.390
But you would think that there would be a measure of respect that would attach to the job.

15:51.211 --> 15:54.475
I'd charge them before God.

15:55.356 --> 16:08.274
And make sure that you do so in such a way that they realize that it is absolutely vital that they're not a quarrelsome group of people there in Ephesus, not quarreling about words because it actually does no good.

16:08.898 --> 16:11.161
Now, that's pretty straightforward, isn't it?

16:11.221 --> 16:12.923
Why shouldn't they be quarreling about words?

16:13.163 --> 16:14.785
Well, it doesn't any doesn't do any good.

16:15.646 --> 16:17.027
That's a good reason, isn't it?

16:17.628 --> 16:19.130
Why waste your time and waste your breath?

16:19.870 --> 16:28.440
The people of God are not to be engaged in tearing each other up, but actually in building each other up, that's Ephesians 4, and also it actually ruins the hearers.

16:29.521 --> 16:32.545
When the people are listening to those kind of arguments, they're just ruined by it.

16:32.845 --> 16:35.028
The word in Greek is actually catastrophe.

16:35.889 --> 16:37.010
It's a catastrophe.

16:37.730 --> 16:52.907
It's a catastrophe when older people who apparently love Jesus and should know better, gather in little clusters in local fellowships and talk in such a way that is quarrelsome and unhelpful and ruinous, and it impinges upon the generation that is coming up behind them.

16:53.668 --> 16:56.111
Because people get like their forebears.

16:56.711 --> 17:06.162
And if you grow up in a church that is marked by quarrelsome-ness, about peripheral issues, unless you leave, you will become like that as well.

17:07.618 --> 17:10.301
You see, Paul is very concerned about these things.

17:11.602 --> 17:14.566
And he comes back to it in verse 16, but I told you we won't go there.

17:15.326 --> 17:20.612
And so we won't, because I said we wouldn't, and I'm a man of my word.

17:21.493 --> 17:36.850
But you check and see whether you can find sad and glaring examples of places where the central issues of the gospel become peripheral, and as a result, the peripheral issues become central.

17:38.018 --> 17:43.024
Remind them and then, secondly and more briefly, present yourself.

17:43.745 --> 17:47.290
Now, once again, present yourself to God as one approved.

17:47.950 --> 17:54.979
Some of us are having a dreadful time or will have a dreadful time in the church because we want to present ourselves to everyone other than God as one approved.

17:55.540 --> 17:56.962
We want the approval of everybody.

17:57.783 --> 18:01.768
We can't have the approval of everybody unless you're just a complete walking disaster.

18:02.689 --> 18:06.834
If you're going to hold the line on anything at all, you will not have everyone's approval.

18:07.362 --> 18:08.243
You recognize that?

18:08.304 --> 18:15.175
No, the concern, Timothy, is that you would be approved by God, that you would present yourself to God.

18:16.217 --> 18:19.201
Keep a close watch on yourself.

18:19.262 --> 18:20.784
Keep a close watch on your teaching.

18:21.044 --> 18:23.088
He said that when he wrote to him in his first letter.

18:23.709 --> 18:34.226
Make sure that you are consistently and persistently in this pathway, because in this pathway lies salvation both for you, Timothy, and for your people.

18:35.618 --> 18:59.405
Charles Simeon, who was a minister in Cambridge for a very long time for 54 years, at the beginning of his ministry, and he was a very gifted fellow from the very outset, at the beginning of his ministry, a man in his congregation, John Thornton, a wealthy man, a benefactor of good causes in 19th century England, wrote to his pastor this note, part of which reads as follows.

19:00.406 --> 19:04.210
Charles, watch continually over your own spirit.

19:05.218 --> 19:06.940
and do all in love.

19:08.102 --> 19:12.609
We must grow downwards in humility to soar heavenward.

19:13.650 --> 19:18.237
I should recommend you're having a watchful eye over yourself.

19:19.539 --> 19:27.009
For generally speaking, as is the minister, so are the people.

19:29.433 --> 19:33.138
Remind them by what yourself, Paul,

19:33.314 --> 19:39.123
was able to say this because he provided such an amazing example for Timothy.

19:39.564 --> 19:48.879
Remember when he writes to the Corinthians, he says, according to the grace of God, given to me, like a skilled master builder, I laid a foundation, and someone else is building on it.

19:50.121 --> 20:00.978
And Timothy now, as you present yourself to God, you do so as a worker, and there can be no excuse, he says, for slipshod half-hearted endeavor in the service of God.

20:01.346 --> 20:05.531
you need to be making sure that you're aiming for the approval of God.

20:06.512 --> 20:12.038
And again and again, Paul has been able to model this before Timothy.

20:13.220 --> 20:22.530
And the distinguishing feature you will notice of the approved workmen is the manner in which he handles the scriptures.

20:23.612 --> 20:29.298
Do your best to present yourself to God as one approved a worker who has no need to be ashamed

20:30.146 --> 20:32.810
rightly handling the word of truth.

20:34.252 --> 20:38.519
So there must be a right way and a wrong way to handle the Bible, right?

20:39.921 --> 20:41.303
We know that in terms of exposition.

20:41.323 --> 20:43.446
Some of us use the Bible as a trampoline.

20:44.488 --> 20:50.116
We get a couple of verses, and we bounce up and down on them for as long as anybody can bear, and then we go on our way.

20:50.176 --> 20:56.245
And the person sitting in the pews says to his wife, what was that about?

20:57.727 --> 20:59.410
And his wife says, nothing.

21:00.578 --> 21:02.340
And he says, I thought so.

21:05.184 --> 21:21.726
Rightly handling the word of truth, not tampering with it, not diluting it, not distorting it, not fiddling it with it, not seeing to press it like a plasticine nose into a shape that we want, but rather the servants of the word.

21:22.868 --> 21:30.418
The unashamed workman doesn't set out to impress, but to instruct, not to bamboozle, but to clarify,

21:31.618 --> 21:41.074
And no matter how good you may be or I may be with words, there is no way that our words can pierce the hearts of men and women.

21:41.094 --> 21:50.149
We may stir, we may excite, we may annoy, we may intrigue, but we can't save.

21:53.294 --> 21:57.842
And it is, as Gresham-Machin says in one of his books,

21:58.146 --> 22:02.550
It is with the open Bible that the real Christian preacher comes before the congregation.

22:03.491 --> 22:05.593
He does not come to present his own opinions.

22:06.374 --> 22:10.098
He comes to set forward what is contained in the Word of God.

22:11.619 --> 22:20.788
In other words, he comes to tell the story of unseen things above, of Jesus and his glory, of Jesus and his love.

22:21.950 --> 22:26.514
I love to tell the story because I know it's true.

22:27.298 --> 22:30.261
It satisfied my longings, like nothing else can do.

22:31.883 --> 22:33.405
I've been doing this for a long time now.

22:33.725 --> 22:34.706
I was ordained at 24.

22:35.047 --> 22:36.168
I'm 62 today.

22:37.229 --> 22:38.210
Not my birthday today.

22:39.131 --> 22:39.952
I'm 62 in May.

22:40.613 --> 22:43.837
But because I was 62 in May and I'm still alive, I'm still 62.

22:44.017 --> 22:55.890
I don't say that to impress you, but simply to make this point, that if I had the opportunity to start all over again,

22:56.674 --> 22:57.795
I would do it in a moment.

22:58.797 --> 23:07.067
I'm jealous for you, young guys, for the opportunities of the gospel, for the privilege of being a servant of God's Word.

23:08.528 --> 23:26.290
And I urge you, when you have the opportunity, remind them of these essential things of the gospel, and make sure that with God's help you present yourself to God as one approved, because remember

23:27.746 --> 23:38.879
What we are, as McShane said, on our knees in the privacy of our bedrooms is actually what we are and nothing else.

23:41.682 --> 23:49.351
Father, thank you that the Bible shines like a light onto our pathways, stirs our hearts and turns us again and again to Christ.

23:50.152 --> 23:55.058
And as we think about the variety of gift that is represented in this room this morning,

23:55.586 --> 24:14.658
We pray, Lord, that You will help us both to be the receivers of Your truth as it comes to us, and then that You will make us the proclaimers of Your Word in such a way that our hearts might be increasingly conformed to its truth and our lives transformed into the image of the Lord Jesus Christ, in whose name we pray.

24:15.639 --> 24:15.980
Amen.

24:18.404 --> 24:21.970
